  <div class="container">
    <section id="home">
      <h2>Welcome to Indra Jatra</h2>
      <p>
        Indra Jatra is one of the most significant festivals celebrated in Kathmandu, Nepal. 
        Dedicated to Lord Indra, the god of rain and king of heaven, this festival blends 
        religion, culture, and tradition in a grand celebration lasting eight days.
      </p>
    </section>

    <section id="history">
      <h2>History</h2>
      <p>
        The festival was started in the 10th century by King Gunakamadeva to honor Lord Indra. 
        It also marks the beginning of the harvest season and is deeply tied to the cultural 
        heritage of the Newar community of the Kathmandu Valley.
      </p>
    </section>

    <section id="celebration">
      <h2>How It Is Celebrated</h2>
      <p>
        Indra Jatra features masked dances, chariot processions, and the raising of the Lingo 
        (a ceremonial pole). The Living Goddess, Kumari, is taken around Kathmandu in a 
        beautifully decorated chariot, while people light oil lamps, perform traditional dances, 
        and offer prayers.
      </p>
    </section>

    <section id="gallery">
      <h2>Gallery</h2>
